habitat_description:
This species occurs in discontinuous and isolated populations in western and west-central Washington (Brodie 1970; Petranka 1998). Populations are known from the Olympic Mountains of western Washington in Challam, Jefferson, and Gray’s Harbor counties in Washington, the Willapa Hills of southwest Washington in Pacific and Wahkiakum counties, in the Cascade Mountains in west-central Washington in Mason, Pierce, and Lewis counties, and in southern and west-central Washington in Skamania and Thurston counties. Overall, populations are distributed at an elevational range from sea level to 1560 meters (Petranka 1998; Lannoo 2005; Green et al. 2013; Stebbins 2003 (1550m)). Egg deposition sites have been reported to include moss-covered stones in damp locations and in partially rotted wood (Jones 1989; Lannoo 2005). 
Juveniles have been reported about 30 centimeters from the water’s edge (Stebbins 1951), while adults are often found under moist stones and moss in the vicinity of running water and seepages, usually in coniferous forests (Stebbins 1951; Brodie 1970).
